b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Eight pilot programs across 26 states approved"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Archer and Joby begin summer flight trials"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Certification bottleneck finally shows movement"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["After years of certification gridlock, the FAA has finally approved eight pilot programs across 26 states that will let Archer, Joby, and other eVTOL manufacturers begin real-world testing this summer. The ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.transportation.gov","children":"US Department of Transportation announcement"}]," confirms what the industry has been waiting for: actual aircraft in actual airspace, not just simulated flights in controlled environments. This is the tangible output of the White House's Advanced Air Mobility and eVTOL Integration Pilot Program (e-IPP) approved last year—a mechanism designed specifically to unstick a certification process that had been stalled for years. The distinction matters enormously. Demo flights in controlled conditions prove the physics work. They don't prove the economics, safety margins, or regulatory frameworks do. What's changing now is that companies will finally run trials for urban air taxi services, regional passenger transport, cargo operations, emergency medical missions, and autonomous flight technology in real environments."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/faa-greenlights-real-world-air-taxi-testing-across/subtitle.jpg","alt":"From press release to payload: testing begins, but certification remains the real bottleneck","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"From press release to payload: testing begins, but certification remains the real bottleneck"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The use-case spread is telling. Urban air taxi gets the headlines, but cargo and medical operations may be where the technology actually proves viable first. Passenger services require a level of public trust and safety certification that cargo flights simply don't—and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.engadget.com","children":"eVTOL battery constraints"}]," make short-haul logistics more realistic than cross-city commuter runs. Scale-up friction remains the real story here. The hardware exists. The physics work. What's delayed deployment isn't engineering—it's certification, infrastructure, and the unglamorous work of proving reliability across thousands of flights, not dozens. According to available information, the testing will \"fundamentally improve\" how transportation systems operate. Maybe. But in aviation, improvement is measured in decades, not press releases. The gap between a successful test program and a commercial service is measured in regulatory filings, maintenance protocols, and infrastructure buildout—not engineering breakthroughs."]}]]}]
